data.content:
Here are better MSTest assertions for your test:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Use Assert.AreEqual for exact count — gives "Expected:3 Actual:5" on failure
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Assert.IsTrue with LINQ is fine, but add a message for diagnostics
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");

    // Use Assert.IsNotNull instead of Assert.IsTrue(x != null)
    var admin = users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, x.Count)` | Exact expected value; clearer failure message |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, x.Count)` | Shows expected vs actual on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` | Semantic clarity; better failure message |

Also useful — `CollectionAssert` for list-level checks:

```csharp
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(users);
CollectionAssert.Contains(users, expectedUser);
CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expectedList, users); // same items, any order
```

The biggest win: when a test fails, `Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count)` reports *"Expected:<3> Actual:<1>"* while `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count == 3)` only says *"Assert.IsTrue failed"*.
